Surprised? “Stunned” is more like it─I even left the bar unattended when I rushed out to take a look. The first night sky in a hundred years, and I could barely see it for the tears in my eyes...
Have you spoken to our hunters yet? I'm still waiting on one of you to take down a Virtue, and bring glory to the Stairs!
The Exarch tells me that you and he share a homeland...so I'm thinking that makes you more than some simple traveler.
Not that I mean to pry, you understand. I'm just hoping you'll be there to even the odds when push comes to shove with Eulmore.
Ah,  . Fancy a cup of mulled wine? After hearing about that Lakeland Warden, I heated up a few bottles for the customers─you know, something to soothe the nerves.
Things seem to have calmed down with the eaters, so the Stairs is back to business as usual. Why don't you stay and have a pint, if you're not too busy?
The sky... That beautiful night sky... We only had it for a short while, but by the shadow do I miss it...
A good, strong pint to see you down the road? ...Ah, best not, eh? You'll need your wits about you by the sound of things.
Tell you what: I'll put aside one of my finest bottles, and you can have a bracing victory drink when you return!
Welcome back! I don't know exactly what you did, but I do know we owe you thanks for bringing the stars back to our skies!
Even with the Light gone, though, it seems the stray eaters didn't get the message. Not that I'm asking you to run around and slay them all yourself, of course...
All hail the great hunter! Things have certainly changed around here since you first walked in─Cyella's attitude not least of all.

That lass always seemed to have a cloud hanging over her, as much as she tried to hide it, but now I see her laughing and talking with the customers like she actually enjoys it. Stranger things, I suppose...
I tell you, Glynard's too nice for his own good. Letting regulars run up tabs and holding off on calling in debts. This is a business, not a charity...

So the night comes, which is bloody grand, but then he goes and shouts, “Drinks on the house for the next hour,” which is bloody mad. How does Glynard expect us to stay afloat with him making gestures like that?
Easy come, easy go. I half expected things to take a turn for the worse, so it's not much to me, but I spied Glynard alone in the storeroom the other day, wiping tears from his face...

Glynard seems to have pulled himself together, thank the gods. Seeing him moping about was starting to wear on me. Bad as it'd be for the coffers, I'd welcome an occasion for him to offer free drink again.
Well, it happened. The night reclaimed, the Warriors of Darkness triumphant, drinks on the house. We'll pay for it later, but for now...at least Glynard got his moment.
Head south from here, and you'll reach Amh Araeng. To the west lies the village of Sullen. Whichever way you mean to travel, be wary. The open road's a dangerous place to be these days.
They call this place the Bridges. Why, you say? Well, do you see that rock formation above us? What does it look like to you?

The vast wood that stretches out before the gate is known as the Forest of the Lost Shepherd. Legend has it that long ago, a young shepherd set out into the woods to find a missing lamb, but never returned.
Quite a sight of the Crystal Tower to be had from here, eh? Take a moment to appreciate it before you move on.

The Exarch Gate─that's what they call the stretch of land ahead of us, you see─is the de facto front doorstep of the Crystarium. It's stoutly protected by a number of strongholds, first and foremost of which is Fort Jobb.
The road north from here will lead you to Holminster Switch. Turn off the road midway there and you'll find the Rak'tika Greatwood, but you'd be wise not to venture too deep within.

South of here lies the ruin known as the Mortal Irons, erstwhile home to the wardens of the Hour of Certain Durance. Tales say it was once known by a less somber name. Either way, I get the chills just thinking about it.

Travel north along this path and you'll reach the ruin known as the Stay. It was once a proud fort built by the elves in the days when they still ruled, to defend Lakeland from an invasion by the Kingdom of Voeburt.
Lali-ho! Following the road here will take you towards Komra...and those sulphur-licking Goggs. Honestly, I'm not sure why we even bothered to make this path...
Lali-hooo! Welcome to Tomra, home of the Tholls! Behave yourself in town, or we'll strap you down and leave you for the knockers. Have a nice day!
Lali-ho! There ain't much north of Tomra but Mt. Gulg itself. And I don't advise you to go up there without a full team of miners at your back...
The good thing about guarding this place is that the desert creatures take care of most would-be bandits. That just leaves the beasts themselves...
Are you heading to Mord Souq? It's that place with the big tower on the other side of the ravine. And watch out for the gigantenders!
If you're crossing the desert, try to stick close to the rocky outcrops. There are all sorts of nasty things lurking beneath the sand...
We're surrounded by remnants of the old Nabaath Empire. Some even say the ghilman are the wandering souls of their dead. You know, I've always felt this is no place for the living...
I know they're up to something. I know it. But I cannot simply leave the periphery unobserved while I go and get a closer look!
In order to undertake the quest “Fear and Delight,” you must first complete the quest “It's Probably Pirates.”
What do the fiends want? What keeps them coming back year after year? I need to know...
What can we do for you this fine All Saints' Wake? Are you here for chills? Thrills? Cookies? We do have cookies.
I can hardly wait to see how dreadful the ahriman's gaze has become by next year's All Saints' Wake! Ah, it sends shivers down my spine just to think of it!
Well, I certainly hope that you two are happy together. Hmph.
Hello there, darling! I hope you're having a properly frightful time! If you're not, well─let me know. I'm sure that I can fix that right up!
I'm sorry madamsir, but we can fit not a single additional morta─er, guest in the mansion at the moment.
Folks ought to keep busy, that's my motto. Idle hands are the fae's playthings.
Wicked white, if you start pestering me like those twins to get inside... <sigh> I tell you, what's the point of being a guard if you can't profit off it? Why would anyone ever take this job?
What kind of things could one find in a machine graveyard, anyway...? Gah, I have to know! Maybe I'll sneak into Komra my very own self...
<squeal> <squeal>
It seems to be saying, “Give me milk.”
<squeal> <squeal>
It seems to be saying, “The marble is pretty. Thank you.”
<squeal> <squeal> <squeal>
It seems to be saying, “I found my friends. Thank you.”
Yes, yeees... Our plans for world domination are proceeding apace...
Heh heh heh... And should anyone attempt to interfere, we will attend to them with great prejudice, heh heh heh...
We had always hoped the allies of Ronka would someday come, that our duty to the emperor might be fulfilled. Now that you are here, I am honestly not sure what to think.
The Eulmorans will pay dearly for what they have done.
It was foretold that one day you would come to our village, but never did we imagine your coming would return the night sky to us. We are forever in your debt.
I... I do not understand. Why has the Light returned? Was what we saw before a trick of the sin eaters?
So this is the sky as it was before the Flood? The sun, moon, and stars are all quite beautiful. I pray the Light does not return to obscure them from our sight.
Do you feel that? The breeze blows toward the Morning Stars. A good omen. After a long day on patrol, sleep comes easy knowing the gods smile upon us.
The Eulmoran soldiers are unlike anything I have ever seen. Their leader especially. To outpace even our swiftest hunters... He is not to be taken lightly.
Have you seen the sky? I know not how, but the Light is gone! For the first time since the Flood, we can all enjoy a good night's rest.
To think the sky was so beautiful such a short time ago...
I had always wondered what it would be like to sleep under the gentle light of a full moon. I cannot say I have ever slept so soundly.
You retrieved the seal of Ronka from the Covered Halls of Dwatl, is that right? I am told it was quite beautiful in the days of the empire. Would that I could see it for myself.
Had the Eulmorans not retreated, I would have gladly put each and every one to the sword.
On occasion the texts of Ronkan history would mention the night sky. But I see now that words do little to capture its splendor.
The texts of the ancients of foretold much of what has and will happen, but nothing of these recent changes in the sky. Perhaps I overlooked something.
Fanow has changed much since your arrival. Perhaps one day I will be permitted to leave and visit the ruins of the Citia Swamps.
Your coming was foretold long ago, and yet still we were unprepared for your arrival. Judging by your dress, the world beyond the Greatwood has seen much change. Much change indeed.
That the Eulmorans would not only trespass in these woods, but infiltrate our temples... It is a shame we will carry for many, many years. I pray we may someday make amends for this disgrace.
You found a Lightwarden beyond the Qitana Ravel? It chose its nest well, for no one─not even we, its protectors─would ever step foot there.
Our life here in the Greatwood has remained unchanging for so long, it is strange to see so much happen so quickly. I can but wonder if we will be able to keep up.
It seems we are at last entering an age of peace. Nevertheless, we must remain vigilant in guarding the ruins. The knowledge within must not fall into the wrong hands.
No doubt you have noticed the winding trails of azure flowers throughout the woods. We call them the Steps of Maja, for it was along those paths Her footfalls gave rise to the flowers you see today.
It is said one will receive Her protection by walking along those paths. And to that end I bid you walk in the Steps of Maja, ally of Ronka, and may Her blessings be upon you.

It was not until the blazing skies above dissipated that I realized the true beauty of the Steps of Maja. Watch the flowers at night, and you will see them glow with Her blessing. It is how She helps guide us in the dark.
Be welcome, ally of Ronka. If there is anything you would ask of us, do not hesitate to ask.

The ravine above which our village was built is called the Ox'Dalan Gap, so named in reverence to the god of death. As you might surmise from its name, none who have fallen into its depths has survived. So do be careful.
Seeing how much Phyna and Ciuna have grown, I am quite confident our future will be in good hands.
Establishing open relations with Slitherbough will require significant change for my people, but ultimately I believe it will be for the better good.
The night sky is so beautiful. It has been so long since I last beheld it, I had nearly forgotten...
I still remember that fateful day when Light claimed the sky. I never thought I would live to endure such misery twice...
When the younglings asked me to describe the night sky, I had always been at a loss for words. But now, thanks to you, they need only gaze up at the heavens.

Though often uneventful, patrol of the ruins can be exhausting. And worse, I have yet to eat today.
I should have hunted a stag before I returned...
With darkness returned to the world, and our duty to the emperor fulfilled, perhaps we can afford to be less stringent in our patrols. I think we all could do with a short rest.

My apologies for our informal welcome. It was a dream of mine to prepare a feast for the allies of Ronka should they one day arrive to our village. But your arrival was so unexpected, I had no time to prepare.
Your defeat of the Lightwarden is what returned the night to us, is it not? We should feast to celebrate! Oh, but what should I prepare for such a momentous occasion? Hmmm...
The Light has returned, and we have yet to even celebrate its retreat. What am I to do with all this food now?
The Night's Blessed have told me of all manner of wonderful foods found beyond the Greatwood. What I would not give to try them.
We live a good life here in Fanow. A simple life. So long as we keep watch of the ruins, the woods will provide for us.
There is talk of trade with the Night's Blessed. Perhaps even the Crystarium. These are strange times for Fanow. But also quite interesting.
After a long day on patrol, it is not uncommon for those on duty to stop at Bowrest. The tents and provisions are sufficient to rest before returning to Fanow.
Bowrest is meant to be a place to repose after patrol, but recently we have been gathering there to simply gaze up at the stars.
People from all walks of life are welcome among the Night's Blessed. Our faith in the Dark is infinitely greater than the sum of our differences.
The soldiers ruined our crops when they trampled through the village. I pray our emergency stores will last until we can grow more.
It should go without saying we were overjoyed to see the return of the night sky, but I did not stop to consider the bounty of the sun. Our gardens have never looked better.
Though the Light has returned, we will not be discouraged. Darkness will prevail.
Nothing gives me greater joy than to sit down for dinner with my fellow Blessed under a starry sky. Truly we are blessed in every sense of the word.
All are welcome here at Slitherbough, though there have been few if any newcomers since the attack on Fort Gohn.
Time and again we have refused the overtures of Eulmore, but now that the Children have joined them... This bodes ill for the Greatwood.
The night sky is more breathtaking than I dared imagine. Would that Toddia were here to see it, but I take comfort in knowing she smiles down upon us from the sunless sea.
The Light's return is a test of our faith, but we shall not be broken.
Our faith in the Dark has been rewarded, and balance has at last been struck with the Light. I very much look forward to seeing what the future holds for our people.
Have you heard? The Warrior of Darkness has returned night to Lakeland and Il Mheg! I imagine it won't be long before the prayers of the Greatwood are answered as well.
All my life I have prayed for the night's return, but I never thought I would live to see it.
I fear some ill fate has befallen the Warrior of Darkness. What else could explain the Light's return?
Praise be to the Warrior of Darkness! The night sky has returned, no doubt by their doing.
I realize they are not a god to be worshipped, but such selflessness is deserving of veneration.
I still remember when I first came here as a child. Everyone was still dressed in garbs of all sorts and colors. We'd yet to find any sense of community back then.
My sight is too far gone to see the stars, but I can feel it─the cool air, the tender touch of the moonlight. It calls to mind the bedtime stories my parents would tell me.
The air has grown foul with the Light's presence again. I do not like it. No, not at all...
The quiet of Slitherbough has given way to the sounds of joy and excitement. Especially the children. Each night they tell me what they can see, and in turn I try to teach them of constellations.
Compared to the guardians of Yx'Maja, we are but children newly come to the Greatwood. But they leave us be, so long as we keep away from their territory.
We have always maintained a rather uneasy coexistence with the Children, but with the weight of Eulmore now behind them, I fear for the Greatwood.

I am as happy as any of the Night's Blessed to see the return of the Dark, but we mustn't grow complacent. The night is not without its dangers, and the Children would not hesitate to take advantage of our indolence.

In the short time we were able to enjoy the night sky, I learned much of how our defenses were lacking. I have faith the Dark will return. And when it does, our guard shall be duly prepared to keep Slitherbough safe.

There has been an influx of volunteers for the night guard. There is no doubt in my mind that many of them only seek an excuse to gaze up at the stars... But if it fills our ranks, I suppose I can allow it.

A great many of the plants near Slitherbough can be used to make dye. Though but tatters of their former glory, the purple standards surrounding the village's entrance are a testament to the abundance of materials at our disposal.
With the threat of sin eaters largely gone, we may resume the rebuilding of Fort Gohn in earnest. I certainly hope you will be here to see it.
We use these jugs to produce yeast. Of all the goods we have to trade, it is perhaps the most valuable.
The roads are much safer than they used to be, meaning trade has increased substantially. We can scarcely keep up with the demand for our yeast.

We may appear secluded here in the Greatwood, but we do, on occasion, trade with the Crystarium and Mord Souq. Dyed goods for pottery, yeast for meats and other foodstuffs. Only what we find absolutely necessary.
The threat of sin eaters is not what it once was, meaning more traders traveling to Slitherbough. We are a simple people, but I cannot help but wonder how this might affect us.
The unchanging sky makes it difficult to judge the passing of time. That is why it's so important to have our meals at the same time each day, to help our bodies maintain their natural rhythm.
I cannot believe Eulmore would willingly aid those zealots of Woven Oath. What are we to do when they return?
Looking up at the sky, it feels as though time has taken its first steps forward since the Flood.
The stagnant sky returns to torment us, but we mustn't lose hope. The Warrior of Darkness will set things right.

When I was a girl, my great-grandmother would tell me stories of a time before the Flood. They always ended with a setting sun, and the hero living happily ever after. Finally it's our turn to have a happy ending.
My brother and I came here two years ago after the great fire. It still hurts to think of home, and all that we've lost.
I never realized how much I detest the Light until the skies turned that horrible shade of primordial white. When I see it I can only think of the sin eaters that attacked our home.

There's a renewed interest in rebuilding Fort Gohn. In fact, some of the Night's Blessed have left to the Crystarium to train and become craftsman. I could never do anything so adventurous as that, but mark my words: I will find a way to help.
Was it fate that brought you to usss...?
Chosen of the ancient ones... Were you welcomed into the illuminated land?
The ancients have blessed us with protection and prosperity. If your presence ssserves to bring us the sssame, there will be no doubt in the matter.
You are the chosen of the ancients. I knew it to be so...
You are a visitor to the Crystarium? Feel free to wander the Rookery, but keep an eye on the amaro─some of them bite.
How fared you in Kholusia? Have you grown accustomed to our amaro mounts?
You know our oceans now, yes? Do you not find it apt that the night sky has ever been known as the sunless sea?
You seem much preoccupied,  . I appreciate the deeds you do for the city, but one who tires herhis wings overmuch risks falling from the sky.
Blessed shadow keep us!
We witnessed your bravery,  . Full many citizens are alive now thanks to your swift actions. You have our gratitude.
It is good to see you returned to us. You are recovered from your injuries, then...?
I pray you find the Exarch. We owe him everything─the Crystarium would not exist without his boundless compassion.
My fellow tamers and I will keep an eye on the horizon. Should the need arise, we shall speed to your side with a flock of amaro in tow.
You have brought back the night itself, and still you flutter to and fro. The Exarch, at least, seems amused to see you thus engaged.
I'm fine... I can still─ I'm fine...
! When did you come back to the First? I trust Tataru and the others are well?
For myself, I decided to stay here for a time, and have been doing what I can to help Eulmore adjust in the aftermath of Vauthry's tyranny.
...And in the spare moments I've had, I managed to finish that painting for Lord and Lady Chai. Considering all they have done, and all that lies ahead, it seemed a suitable gesture.
!? No one told me you were back!
Well, never mind that. You should try speaking with Halric!
I've come to believe that some miracles simply require an inordinate amount of stubbornness. That goes for your case, for Halric's...and I'm hoping for Ga Bu's as well!
There you are. I take it there were no pressing matters to keep you in the Source, then?
If not, I may have need of you in the near future. There is still yet so much to be learned of this world. So many mysteries begging to be solved.
The greatest perhaps being the truth of Emet-Selch's words that fateful day in the Qitana Ravel. A most troubling matter to be sure, but remember: it is not a burden you must bear alone.
Hm? If you've come looking for work, I might have a spot for another guard.
Ah, it's good to be back. Mord Souq has many charms, but there's nothing like a proper bed to recover from a long journey...as I'm sure you'd agree.
The return of night's wreaked havoc on demand, and as it turns out, it can be dangerous to travel in the dark. It'll take some getting used to...but that beautiful, starry sky is worth it.
They say the Eulmoran Army's headed for the Crystarium. This can't end well...
Sin eaters are coming! A whole bloody horde of them! I'm no warrior, but I'll help any way I can─even if that means carrying arrows to the front lines!
I saw you,  ─saw you fighting the eaters on the front lines. That was impressive stuff.
!? I thought you were bedridden!
While we're on the subject, I'm concerned for that Alisaie of yours. I'd thought her face stormy on that ride back from Amh Araeng, but now...it's closer to a raging tempest.
I might offer some words of encouragement to the masses while I'm out and about on business. You need proper support to do what you need to do, and we can't let morale start flagging now, can we?
, good to see you well. Of late, I can't help but remember our trip to the desert together. Feels like only yesterday, it does...
Yes, sweetie? Does something hurt?
The night is lovely and all, but do watch your step in the dark, yes? Why, not a moment ago I had to apply some very bracing ointment on a skinned knee.
Oh? You liked the taste so much, you want some more, is that it? Hee hee, you are a strange one!
Oh dear, we've never seen so many sin eaters before... We must make ready to receive the wounded.
Don't worry about the wounded, sweetie. We'll make sure they do not want for care.
Oh, sweetie! You had us all so worried!
I wish I could brew you a tonic, sweetie, but I've no idea how it might affect you...
...No, it's too dangerous. In the end, I can but pray for your well-being. May blessed shadow keep you, your friends, and the Exarch as well.
Hm? Do you need a tonic for your travels, sweetie? Oh, and maybe you should take one for the Exarch as well. Invigorating stuff if you can abide the smell...

Oh, sweetie, it's good to see you hale and whole! Whenever you're under the weather, don't hesitate to come here, yes? I'm sure we can find a tonic to perk you right up. No promises as to the taste, though. Hee hee!
<squeal> <squeal>
It seems to be saying, “I love milk. Thank you.”
I'm always pleased to welcome a new arrival. When the population swells, more goods start moving, and more trade means more growth...
Standing here, in the middle of the markets, I can feel the joy that's taken root in the city. Smiling faces everywhere I look─that's what I like to see.
Eulmore's dispatched its military, has it? I'll see that we won't be stuck for supplies. Better to be ready for the worst, than be caught unprepared.
Being in Eulmore's bad books has slowed things down for the markets...but that's for me to worry about. The best thing you can do is go about your business as usual.
If you're going into battle against that swarm of eaters, I suggest you stock up on potions and the like. And if you've any holes in your boots, now's the time to get them repaired!
Medical supplies are selling as soon as we stock them, but the shelves are still heavy with foodstuffs and clothing. So many who won't be coming home...
We'll need to invite the Eulmorans back to the bargaining table... Just a shame that it took something like this to bring them to their senses.
You still look a little worse for wear, my friend. If you can't stay abed, you should at least find yourself a nice, hot cup of tea or something...
All stocked up on supplies then? Better to have it and not need it, than need it and not have it, as my old man used to say. Be safe, and bring the Exarch back to us...
The question I hear most in the markets these days is, “What does the Warrior of Darkness buy?” Everyone wants to emulate their hero, right down to herhis shopping list.
Not that our shopkeeps ever give them a straight answer, of course. We don't betray the privacy of our valued customers, let alone our dear friends.
I've been keeping that device you uncovered safe and sound. Did you need to use it again...?
The portal that brought you here has not yet closed. Were you to reach out and touch it, you would most likely be returned to the Source.
Do you wish to fly to Kholusia? Stormy skies or ocean gales, my hand-raised amaro soar swift and true!
Do you have business with the Crystal Exarch? Just say the word, and I would be happy to escort you to the Ocular.
Bound for Amh Araeng, are you? I can ready an amaro that knows its way around the desert currents.
You wish to ascend to the Canopy? Why, yes, this lift will take you there.
You wish to descend to the Buttress? I'll call the lift for you, then.
Any time you need it, the Ladder is at your service. Heading up to Top Rung, then?
It is now my proud duty to serve as a Ladder operator. If you wish to descend, I'll tell the lads down below to get those gears turning!
Back to the ocean floor, is it? ...Oh no, I'll just be rowin' you out into the bay. When it comes to gettin' down to the bottom, you're on your own, mate!
Flying back to the Crystarium, misssir? It's perfectly safe─our amaro are swift and strong enough to escape any stray eater.
Your first order of business will be to reunite with Alphinaud and Alisaie. In so doing, the predicament here in Norvrandt should become abundantly clear.
As for communications with the Source, Feo Ul will gladly serve as your messenger. If needs be, however, you yourself should be capable of making the journey between worlds.
The device there will serve as a portal─simply touching a hand to its surface will transport you to the location of the beacon I left at the base of the tower. In theory, at least...
Back so soon, my friend? In case you were worried about us, do not be. All is well here.
On the contrary, I worry about you. The faeries are a mercurial folk who possess their own customs, far departed from those of men.
So pray focus on the task at hand, and nothing else. Rest assured that the Crystarium will still be standing upon your return.
I still remember the day my misguided attempts to summon you here drew Thancred to the First. When the realization of where he was dawned on him, the very first words from his mouth were of Minfilia.
'Tis not my place to speak of his struggles, but I pray that─when this is all over─he finds what he was looking for here in the First.

My informants have kept me abreast of the situation in Eulmore, and it does not bode well for us, I'm afraid. If you should have need of reinforcements, rest assured they shall be sent with all haste.

So long as we are in their realm, we must expect to be subjected to the faeries' mischief. Indeed, Minfilia and I have experienced more than our fair share of it. From the harmless to the downright murderous, we've seen it all.
Reasons notwithstanding, to live here for as long as Urianger has requires no small amount of forbearance. In that regard, he is a better man than I.
If the pixies offer to take you somewhere, take them up on it at your peril.
...That's the very first thing Urianger taught me.
I was asked to retrieve a garland from a tree branch. “The wind blew it there,” the pixie claimed. Questionable premise aside, the dragoon's jump would have been useful for this task...
So, I'm supposed to bring them a plank of wood. That has no wood grain. Hah hah hah...
You found Alisaie, then? I would've loved to have seen her reaction... Ah, but had I been there, she would've put on her stoic face!
...? I thought you were out with Alisaie?
Whenever I come to the Crystarium, the sands of Amh Araeng seem a world away. And yet they both lie under this same, wretched sky...
I will do what I can to decipher the tablet's contents as quickly as I can. Though I fear it will require time we can ill afford, even with Urianger's help.
In my time here, I read through texts covering all manner of topics regarding the Ronkan Empire, but there was surprisingly very little pertaining to linguistics.
I suspect they were lost in the chaos that ensued at the time of the Flood. If there were a word to describe such a terrible loss of knowledge, it is one we will now never know.
When Y'shtola first arrived in the First, she made swift work of the Cabinet of Curiosity. Her thirst yet unsated, she then journeyed hither seeking the wisdom of Ronka.
She found little in the way of welcome from the Blessed, however. 'Twas not until the great fire, where she denied the sin eaters a feast of aether, that she gained their trust.
Since then I have served as liaison 'twixt Slitherbough and the Crystarium, that she might be kept abreast of the others' efforts.
Proceed to Woven Oath with caution, I prithee. Should the Children find thee, they will not suffer thee to leave.
Do not be reckless. We would be glad to have her heartstone returned to us, but it is not worth both of your lives.
I had no right to involve you in our troubles. Still, without your help, today's service would not have been possible. The Night's Blessed are in your debt.
I realize there is no stopping you, so do what you must, and the Night's Blessed shall do the same.
I only ask that you keep Master Matoya safe. There is no denying she is powerful, but the path she needs is plain. Where she goes, she will have need of powerful allies.
You are returned! Where are Master Matoya and the others?
Master Matoya was only with us for two years, but she will remain in our hearts for a lifetime.
Safe travels, my friend. We will keep you all in our prayers.
! It is a relief to see you up and about, my friend. When Master Matoya came and told us what happened... I have never seen her so stricken with grief. We feared for the worst.
All things considered, we have done quite well since you were last here, but I fear your concern is misplaced. Such an ordeal has surely taken its toll on you. Please, go and rest.
Ah, the mighty hero returns to grace Slitherbough with herhis presence. When the night sky returned, we knew at once that all would be right with the world.
Any doubts we may have had were quickly put to rest when Master Matoya came. It did my heart good to see her in such high spirits.
We should hold a feast to celebrate your victory. Then you can finally sample my famous stew!
. What brings an ally of Ronka to Fanow?
If there is aught you need, but ask and the Viis will answer.
We recently received one of your comrades, who made a most unusual request. They asked of a magic that could alter one's “elemental affinity.”
They scoured the ruins and pored over every tome we could find. Alas... Before they left, we also provided them with drawings of the Qitana Ravel's murals. I pray they might be of use to you.
Welcome, ally of Ronka. Your companion Y'shtola was here not long ago. It would seem the mural drawing was of use. She came to thank us, but it is we who must thank you.
We but did our duty to the allies of Ronka, and by your deeds the world has been returned to balance. On behalf of all of Fanow, I thank you.
Ah,  . It is good to see you again so soon.
Since your arrival, many of the Viis have grown curious of the outside world. Myself included. Should you be so inclined, we would all very much like to hear of your travels.
Though we did not foresee the return of the blazing skies, your arrival has taught us to expect the unexpected.
The woods have been blissfully quiet of late. I should think all of Norvrandt now enjoys such calm.
It is strange yet somehow exciting to think what will now become of us. Of the world.

You come from the Crystarium, yes? I recently met─or rather, apprehended─a merchant of that city. I had him in my sights, and had every intention of shooting. Yet something compelled me to instead speak with him.
He told me of a place with many different peoples, of a glittering tower that reaches to the heavens. It sounds like a wonderful place.
Has something happened? Aside from the return of the blazing sky, I mean.
Your companion Y'shtola came to us recently, terribly distraught. It shames me to think we were unable to help her.
Quiet and calm have returned to the Greatwood, and it has given me time to think of the future.
The empire of Ronka was vast, and remnants of its greatness reach far beyond the borders of Rak'tika. When the time is right, I wish to see them with my own eyes.
I prithee keep Thancred occupied in thy search for leonine.
Minfilia and I shall see to preparations for the Talos.
The Talos means the world to Magnus, despite what he might say. If you were able to find any leonine, it'd mean more to him than you know.
I wish there was more I could do to help, but I only seem to make things worse...
Gods, you really found it... Maybe with that leonine we can finally get through to Magnus. Help him move on.
First you go and do the impossible digging up that leonine, and now the sky's gone clear as crystal.
I can't rightly say I understand what's happening, but looking up at the sky, I get the feeling it's a change for the better.
! Thank the gods. No sooner had the sky turned to fire than your friends shooed us off with barely an explanation of what's going on.
Thancred eventually stopped by to speak with us, but by the sounds of it you were on death's door not long ago. If I didn't know better, I'd say your luck is starting to run out.
Oh,  . Come to enjoy the scenery? Such that it is...
I can't help but wonder what would've happened had you not found that leonine. If it might've found some other way into your hands.
Oh, Agna... I wish you could've met her. She was a light of hope in the darkness, as strange as that may sound.
If you're heading to Nuvy's Leavings, you'll want to speak with Guthjon. I can't guarantee you'll find what you're after, though...
Back already? ...There wasn't trouble in the mines, was there?
Well, well. Urianger said you'd be too busy to stop by.
I won't ask for details, but I'm fairly certain the change in the sky is your doing. Glad the Talos and trolley could be of help.
Gods,  ! Are you sure you should be up and about right now?
Death doesn't like to be cheated, friend. You need to be careful...
The mighty hero returns, and in better health it seems. I wish there was some way to repay you for all you've done.
Every time I look up at the sky, I am reminded of my wife and my son. Of their dreams now made reality. Would that they were here to see it.
If you want to know more about the gate, you'd be better off asking Jeryk. You can find him over by the tracks, probably daydreaming about trolleys.
There you are. Glad to see you made it out of the well in one piece.
Now that we have a working trolley there's plenty for us to do, but I think I speak for all of us when I say you've earned yourself a rest.
Thancred told us what happened. Are you all right?
I look up at the sky and it feels like I'm dreaming, but it's real. The Light is gone.
Somehow you've made the impossible possible. Though I hope this doesn't give Jeryk any ideas...
Why the long face? ...Oh gods, is it the trolley!?
I've been thinking about what drove the light from the sky, and I think I have an idea. What if, once upon a time...or, I suppose a few days ago.
A young boy, no higher than my knee, sat alone in his room one night, gazing up at the blinding light of the sky. But the light was too much for his delicate eyes, and he went blind.

“Why have the gods forsaken me,” he cried. “Why would they deny me the sight of my beloved trolley?”
The gods heard his cries and, perplexed by the boy's despair, parted the sky to behold the object of his adoration.
<sigh> Just when we fixed the lights working on the tracks, the sky had to go and change back.
I was hoping we'd have something exciting to show you. Maybe another time...
I had the most ingenious idea for a new trolley, but Magnus refuses to listen. Maybe he'd consider if he heard it from you.
Honestly, I don't understand how he can remain unmoved by the clang, clang, clang of the trolley. Or the ding, ding, ding of the bells.
Surely you feel it, don't you? The zing, zing, zing, of your heartstrings...? <sigh> From the moment I first saw these trolleys as a boy, I fell in love with them.
You...wish to return already?
Off you go─the city is yours to explore. Oh, but do be careful along those outer walkways! I should be most upset if you were to slip and fall.
The loyal assistant! Have you come with...? Ah. No. Of course not.
By all means, take care of those “important matters” Alphinaud mentioned, but please─see that he comes back and finishes my painting just as soon as he can!
Oh! Feeling better, are we? I almost fainted in shock when I saw your friends were carrying you down the mountain.
Is there no end in sight to these “important matters” of yours? I should think you've suffered enough by now.
Never mind the sky─I'm more concerned we shall find you collapsed by the side of the road if you keep this up! You must take better care of yourself...
Oooh! Another visitor! How lovely! Will you have a slice of cake and a spot of tea? A light meal, mayhap?
...Ah, but what am I thinking? We cannot lay the table with luxurious abandon as we once did.
Goodness me, 'tis a shame to not have sweets for my sweets─both you and Alphinaud are so adorable! I must be sure to have the larder stocked before your next visit!
...Well, what is it? Spit it out, then!
If my wife has given her permission, then you need not seek my say-so. All I ask is that you behave yourself. Draw no attention, and be respectful at all times!
Wh-What are you─ Have you gone mad!?
We can bribe the guards with favors and such, but up here...? No matter what my wife says, you must leave before you bring disaster down upon all of our heads!
I wonder if making that Talos was truly the right thing to do... I hope you've not talked me into something I shall regret.
Some folk are saying the Light is some manner of divine punishment for standing against Vauthry. As for what I think, well...I honestly couldn't tell you anymore.
As you can see, things are back to normal here...aside from, you know, needing to completely restructure the social hierarchy.
But however the matter is resolved, it would seem I must begin working for my crust again. Mayhap I shall revive the Stoneworks, and develop a new Talos for this modern age...
Aye, that ought to keep a smile on the wife's face!
If only every town could share the Crystarium's spirit of independence...
Still, I suppose one cannot decide for others what they should and should not deem important. My powers of persuasion have certainly had little effect on the people of Kholusia...
S-Stay back!
I can't... I can't...
I...I failed them all...
Mother... I don't want to die...
<wheeze>
I-I'm all right, I think. My injuries have been tended to.
If only the others had been as fortunate as I... But there's nothing for it but to continue the fight, is there?
You are bound for the road? The guard keeps this area relatively safe, but take care should your travels take you beyond Lakeland.
Full glad I am to see your safe return, and with the Exarch at your side, no less.
When he has recovered from his ordeal, I mean to ask as many questions as he will allow. And even if he chooses not to answer, well...so be it.
Despite his secretive ways, he never was adept at hiding his feelings. I am content to know him as that same loving─if mysterious─grandfather he has always been to me.
<gasp>
The others have left to search for the beacon. Weren't you joining them?
In the absence of the others, we must manage the affairs of the Rising Stones to the best of our ability. Would that we could do more...
I pray this beacon you spoke of leads you to the others. Gods, where could they be?
I'm holdin' the fort. Someone needs to keep an eye on the Empire after all.
, y-you're back! Have you already finished saving the world!?
...Not quite? Well, if you need to get back to the First, it should be a simple matter of touching the beacon. It's at the same place we found it!
! I was going about my business the other day when a feisty little pixie suddenly appeared and gave me a report about your doings!
It certainly sounds like you have your work cut out for you. So just leave things here to me and focus on getting things done in the First!
Not much to report on our end,  . The Eorzean Alliance is still locked in a stalemate with the Empire.
As ever, in the Archons' absence, I'm keeping the ship that is the Scions of the Seventh Dawn sailing smoothly along. I run a tight ship, I do!
If you are worried about the Archons' bodies, rest assured all is unchanged and well. We here continue taking turns watching over them.
Welcome back,  . How do the Archons fare over in the First? When next you see them, you may inform them that their bodies are as well as can be.
Welcome,  . As you can see, nothing of consequence has happened while you were away. You needn't worry for us.
A pleasure to see you,  ! I cannot well imagine what sort of world the First is, or adventures you had, but that you have returned to us safe and sound is of great comfort...
Arenvald has taken the lead in our efforts to contain the primals.
He is adamant that we hold the fort, leaving you free to pursue greater matters, and the rest of us could not agree more.
Not that I expected any less, but 'tis good to see you home and unharmed. I am pleased to report that Arenvald and his fellow primal hunters have upheld the peace while you've been away.
Together with the Eorzean and Eastern alliances, we've been wagin' our war o' subterfuge in the Empire. Thancred's left big shoes to fill, but I try to fill 'em as best I can.
Our war o' subterfuge is movin' along well enough, but we often find ourselves wantin' for Thancred and Alphinaud's expertise.
Wish they'd hurry up and get their arses back over here...
So, heading south, are you?
We've readied a boat to the tower if you should have need of it.
The Talos sits lifeless, waiting to be repaired...

The art of extracting materia from common items is lost on most citizens of Eulmore, it saddens me to say, as it requires a certain amount of prior knowledge to truly understand its benefits. Perhaps once you have become better versed in the subject, you might like to make use of our expertise.
If you are hoping to convert something into materia, you have come to the right place!
Aye, I've heard about everything from the Scions. To think that Shtola has crossed over to the First...
Well, knowing that girl, she's taking it all in her stride. When next you see her, tell her that I shall expect a visit as soon as she returns.

I recently received word from the Rising Stones regarding the whereabouts of the missing Scions. It would seem their spirits have been whisked away to another world entirely. Assuming you believe such nonsense to be possible.
! I almost had trouble believing the reports Tataru shared with us... How is everyone over there? Is Alphinaud faring well?
If you're worried about things falling apart over here, you should know that we have the primals well in hand. Go and do what you need to do, and take as long as you need!
The light within you shines as brightly as before. More brightly, even. But your journey is far from finished. I shall pray for you.
Oh, dearest, we really should have found you some new gloves.
Yes, my love, you're probably right...
I think Alphinaud looks simply precious in the more frilly fashions, but he seems the most comfortable in traveling wear...
...So I settled on his current wardrobe. It's not a common style in Eulmore, and I can just imagine the heads turning as he strides through the crowd!
I really must have your mentor concentrate on his art. Our anniversary will be upon us soon, and I promised to have a portrait to commemorate our union!
More so than the revelation that Vauthry is a sin eater, I'm surprised that the free citizens of Eulmore came together to work on the Ladder.
Is it possible for people to change so quickly...?
Oh, how I wish you could stay. But I understand that duty calls and you must answer.
Each night when I gaze up at the sunless sea, I will think of you, of Master Matoya, of all you have done for the Night's Blessed. Safe travels, my friend, and may the shadows keep you.
Madbloom or no, we have a new Titania! The king is returned! All hail the king!
If you ever see that wrinkly old man again, pay him back for me ten─nay, a thousandfold!
Did you see the looks on their faces as they ran? Ohhh, it was delicious!
I have no doubt thou wilt find the contents of the tablet most informative.
<sigh> Every time I step out of those mines the sky seems to get brighter. I'd never leave them if the air weren't so stale...
Naught but a Talos can pry open the gate to Nabaath Areng. We must needs speak with the engineers at Twine if we are to open it.
Hm? What's going on here, you say? We'll be holding a musical performance here as part of the Starlight festivities. Why not stay for the show? If you've nothing better to do, that is...
You're the conductor they sent us? You don't look particularly musical. Oh, well. Don't worry if you ruin the show. It's not like anyone's life depends on it.
It appears your audience wants an encore. I have to admit, you weren't nearly as lost up there as I thought you'd be. Anyhow, if you're up for another show, why not speak with Amh?
Come one, come all! A blissful chorus of angelic voices awaits! If you miss this musical performance of a lifetime, you'll regret it for the rest of your days!
Ah, Maestro! I was wondering when you would grace us with your presence. Your adoring audience can scarcely wait to hear what manner of virtuosic performance you have in store for them!
Bravo! Oh, bravo! Do you hear those cheering voices? Your fans simply demand an encore, and─if it is not too bold of me to say so─so do I! Pray speak with Amh if you are willing to oblige.
Come to see the show, have ye? Just between you an' I, we've got a surprise or two lined up for our audience this year. Ye'd best not be missin' it, if ye want my advice.
Tell me,  ─what sort of dreams do you see? If you wish, I can show you the most delightful dreams...unless you prefer something fiendish? Hee hee!

Lyhe Mheg is an illusory realm that lies between dreams and reality. The Fuath used similar magicks to create Dohn Mheg, but our realm is a thousand times better. Why? You're more likely to have fun in it than die, that's why!
My friend was the prettiest of pixies. Even after they became a sin eater, they were pretty. <sigh> How I miss them...
I won't leave you alone again, I promise. So please, hold on...
Come to see the show, have ye? Just between you an' I, we've got a surprise or two lined up for our audience this year. Ye'd best not be missin' it, if ye want my advice.
Aye, that's right. The shinin' stars of this year's show are the Gods' Quiver an' their carolin' chocobo. Hah! Reckon that'll have all the children in town smilin'!
Now that's what I call a show! I'm game for an encore whenever you and yer friends are. We could even perform last year's tune─ye know, for old times' sake.

You needn't concern yourself with affairs here in Eorzea. The situation at the Ghimlyt Dark is well in hand thanks to the Alliance, and our efforts in containing potential primal threats have proven more than effective.
I confess there is not a great deal I can do myself, but I am no less determined to do my part. Which is why I have focused my efforts on recruiting others to join our cause.
Mistress Krile has apprised us of the Archons' present─and unexpected─situation. You may rest assured we will support her in any way we can to keep their bodies safe.
I can scarcely begin to imagine what it will take to bring the others home. But whatever that may be, I know you'll figure it out.
, might I ask a favor of you? I'm not normally one to pry, but F'lhaminn has been oddly distracted ever since you came back to tell us of your travels in the First.
Would you go and see if she's all right?
In caring for the Scions, we've made more than a few new allies. I'm sure they'll be of use in the future once everyone is back safe and sound.

Gods, it seems barely any time has passed since the Archons were whisked away to the First, and yet for them it has been years. I can only imagine how much they have changed. How much stronger they have become.
With Riol now out in the field, I was asked to return to make up for his absence. Alas, Hoary and the others were unable to accompany me.

A great deal of my time was spent poring over tomes of all sorts when I first arrived here in the First, but now I would revisit them, giving greater care to any that may touch on matters of the soul.
Thanks to Beq Lugg and the Crystal Exarch, we at last have a plan on which to focus our efforts.
The time for dwelling on the past has ended. Indeed, if I am to be of help to you and the Archons, I must look toward the future.
I have no doubt the road before you is perilous. But remember─you do not walk alone, my friend.
...<mumble>
The future of Eulmore is at stake, is it? Well, do for them what you can, but keep an eye on Alphinaud, would you? See to it he doesn't involve himself more than is necessary.
Hm? Why did I name my familiar Angelo? It was the name of our pet dog, long, long ago.
Alphinaud wanted to name it after some supposedly important figure in a book no one had ever heard of. Quite the fight, that was. But in the end, I won.
Nothing much has changed here in Amh Araeng. <sigh> Sadly, that includes Jeryk's unbridled enthusiasm for trolleys. Gods help us if people actually begin to listen to him.
If I'm to convince anyone that building a giant trolley is a good idea, I have to explain the benefits of having one. Or at least, that's what I was told the last time I talked to someone about it.
It seems I'm the only one who'd be satisfied to simply marvel at the sight of one. But I'll come up with something. You wait and see.
We've been considering expanding the railway system of late. Being able to ship goods beyond Amh Araeng would be a boon for all of Norvrandt.
...Suitable for a giant Talos? You haven't been talking to Jeryk, have you?

I thought myself duly prepared, but I now find myself far busier than I anticipated. Thankfully there is no shortage of support from the nearby villages, not to mention that of other fine entrepreneurs like Mistress Mowen.

I've made a habit of keeping sweets and tea ready for my dear husband's return. Perhaps more than is necessary... If you should find yourself in need of respite, you are more than welcome to partake of them.
If my darling is to reopen Daedalus Stoneworks, there's little time for sweets and tea─I must ready the ledgers.
I confess, I know very little of the Talos and their inner workings. But numbers, my dear, are where I can play my part.
Master Chai's policies are quite sound. Rest assured that, as his advisor, I will see them carried out with due caution.
Starting to think, maybe...maybe I'll get better...someday. Well enough...to go home...
This warmth in my chest...it's spreading. Can feel it...in my hands...
...<mumble>
Master Chai's talk of a better Eulmore's givin' the people hope, but I'm not convinced. If his plans ain't all they're cracked up to be, there'll be hell to pay. I promise you that.

There's been a sharp increase in volunteers to join the Eulmoran Army. It would not be so surprising if they were not all non-citizens. In truth, I'm beginning to think such distinctions will have little, if any meaning, in the future.

There are still sin eaters wandering about out there, is that right? With Lord Vauthry no longer here to keep them at bay, we will need keep watch of our borders. Meaning we will need more helping hands.

I was given leave to seek a new profession, to depart from Eulmore entirely if I so wanted, but it is quite clear that the exchange of goods will prove crucial to the city's future. And so I choose to remain.
They're saying I'll have to work, and...earn wages to pay for food. Gods... What if I have to pay to stay here in the Beehive!?

Master Chai's words have resonated with the people, and you'll find no clearer example than within the army. Though we are few in number, morale is high, and we have every intention of doing what we can to keep the people safe.
We recently received a missive from Master Chai telling of potential trade between Eulmore and Amity.
The people here are understandably doubtful, some even fearful of Eulmoran influence. But I wish to believe he bears good intentions.
I swear, with enough Talos, I reckon we could do damn near anything. Can you imagine the ship we could run with them? Of course, we'd still need more than a few good men on board to keep course.
Still, it's a mighty fine dream. A grand dream, fit for this new Eulmore everyone's been talking about.

We've a mind to put the Talos to work on fishing boats, maybe even a few merchant ships. And surprisingly, there's been no shortage of helping hands. Never thought I'd see the day when there'd be fresh faces to show the ropes.
Fine mess this is. We're miners! We can't just not dig. But if we keep going and some mechanical monstrosity pops out from underground... We're still just miners!
Your enthusiasm is appreciated, but I haven't any tasks for you at present. Were you not called to settle some pressing matter in Eulmore?
It will take time to create a device suitable to our plans. I'll not deny the allure of the many sights in this city, but rest assured, naught but the task at hand is at the forefront of my mind.

Blue Mage Guild still not have proper building to call home. When Martyn say “return to the guild,” he mean this street corner where we always stand. And “keep guild afloat” mean “put money in Martyn's pocket.”
Martyn always thinking about money, but why he so poor? He only ever buy cheap food, cheap clothes, cheap everything. Where his Masked Carnivale money going?
Martyn is powerful mage, it is true, but maybe Siegfried too strong for Martyn.
This time, Martyn make big wager. But Latool Ja think it strange that Martyn can gamble with the Masked Carnivale. It belong to Royse, no? Why she allow this Latool Ja not understand.
How goes the blue magin'? Got yourself any new spells?

As for me, I've been busy tryin' to make a new name for myself as Azuro the Third. I don't think they've figured out it's still the same old me, though. I did consider gettin' a new costume, but these things cost money, you know.
N...Nect... Al...

Now then, how big should I make the nostrils on this porxie?
...Hm? Please leave me be─I am in the midst of contemplating a serious matter.

I thought the clear blue skies of Ishgard would be the perfect backdrop for learnin' some blue magic, but when I got there, I was in the middle of a bleedin' snowstorm! Still, I'd say it was character buildin', if nothin' else.
Those novices seem to have really taken a shine to you. Don't let all that admiration go to your head, though!
Do you reckon my blue magic'll be able to get through Siegfried's defenses? I suppose I could try cookin' him in his own armor with a bit of Flame Thrower!
I'll tell you what, I'm lookin' forward to getting' this match over and done with, one way or another. It's all the waitin' around before that I can't stand!
Looks like it's all down to you now. One bit of advice: I'd give Self-destruct a miss if I were you. That spell's more trouble than it's worth!
The Queen Bee is normally reluctant to take risks, so I was surprised when he hired Kai-Shirr on the spot!
The Beehive certainly has changed since you and Kai-Shirr started helping about the place. It's great to have customers other than the usual Eulmoran regulars!
Kai-Shirr has always been one to act spontaneously, so I hope you will be able to keep his impulsive streak in check.
The recent changes have brought in a whole host of new customers, which really keeps me on my toes. I've never even heard of some of the drinks they're ordering!
My dear friend shared the dream of making Lyhe Mheg breathtakingly beautiful, and I believe it was their hand that guided An Lad. How delighted they would be to see our garden as it is now!
It's thanks to you that both Lyhe Mheg and An Lad are safe.
And I haven't forgotten that you set my departed friend free either. I don't think I could owe anyone more than I owe you,  .
Lest you wonder, I created Ezel to be my assistant. Its reports on the nightmares it devours have provided me with many an invaluable insight into mortal and fae minds alike.
Ezel has reported to me in detail about your victory over the nightmares. To think that the will of Titania was giving rise to An Lad's dreams... It has given me much food for thought.
I've heard all about you, mortal! Oh, yes! We're going to get along like a leafman on fire, I just know it!
No mortal's ever been allowed to enter Lyhe Mheg before─not outside of their own dreams, at any rate. Consider yourself lucky that Tyr Beq has taken such a shine to you!

I'm sure you're sick of hearing this by now, but thank you for protecting Lyhe Mheg! As Tyr Beq says, An Lad is a little different from the rest of us. But as a fellow pixie, we have far more in common than not, and I look forward to playing with them!
The pixie who was crying in my dreams has left. Wherever they are now, I hope they're happy.
Thanks to everyone's efforts, we're able to keep Lyhe Mheg the beautiful place that it is.
For my part, I'm working on my dreamspinning skills. Creating fun dreams makes Tyr Beq happy...and that makes me happy.
Sorry, but I can't talk right now─I'm preparing to play shopkeep!

Greetings, greetings, and be welcome to my shop! Might I interest you in some stolen or lost or discarded wares?
...Well, what do you think? Do I sound like a real shopkeep?
We now offer porxies, you'll be pleased to hear! As soon as we told Lugg Aenc that you had dire need of the creatures, they whipped up a whole bunch in a hurry!

At last, Ishgard begins to rebuild in earnest. The works will be focused on the Firmament at first, but it must not end there. We must see that all areas of the nation receive the attention they deserve.
Did you hear? They're rebuildin' the Firmament district. Does this mean we'll all have proper homes?
We've all got high hopes for the Firmament, Hilda not least of all. Fairly champin' at the bit to watch over the district, she is.
Some o' ours have put down their arms and picked up buildin' implements instead. Feels like only yesterday that we were feudin' with nobles and fendin' off dragons, but times can change, eh?

Much is being made of the Firmament, but you'll forgive me if I'm not dancing in the street. Somehow I doubt us poor folk will get gilded invitations to live there. Having said that, I'm glad for the work that the reconstruction brings.
Both the Houses of Lords and Commons voted unanimously in favor of the reconstruction of the Firmament.
From creating employment to reviving trade, the motives may have differed between members. Yet in this united motion, I felt a sense of optimism for our nation I hadn't felt before.
You're one of the artisans workin' in the Firmament, aren't you? If you chance to see Lord Francel, do remind him to take his ease from time to time.
Since the reconstruction of the Firmament commenced, the Crozier has been struggling to meet demand. It is a dilemma of the welcome kind.
'Tis mine honor to hold the fort in Lord Francel's absence. So long as this knight lives and breathes, Skyfire Locks will stand firm against all threats.
Conscientious a man as my lord is, he often pays us visit─as does Lord Emmanellain─but they have naught for which they need be concerned.
And just like that, the Light's back... But I'll never forget the sight o' that beautiful night sky. Not till the end o' my days.
Well met, good madamsir. I am the ushi bugyo, come with a delegation from the Far East on a mission to share our customs and traditions with the people of Eorzea.

It is my honor and privilege to share our Heavensturn customs in this, the year of the ox. To mark this momentous occasion, I will be serving traditional sweets to the good people here in Limsa Lominsa. If you would care to sample a taste of the Far East, you need only come and join the celebration.
My thanks again for your assistance in rectifying our mochi problem.
If by some chance the mochi should again attain sentience, I trust we can turn to you for aid?
Bwoo!
Begging your pardons, but aren't you the one who restored the night sky to Il Mheg? If it please you, won't you grant me your patronage?
Recently, I've come into possession of these cards which mortals use in a game. I ask that you play the game with me, and in return I will offer you a fitting payment.

Now then, how big should I make the nostrils on this porxie?
...Hm? Please leave me be─I am in the midst of contemplating a serious matter.
Well, well, it appears I am victorious. I pray you are not upset, and choose to play with me again.
Well, it appears you are victorious. Though this is but a game, I must confess I am disappointed...
It appears we have a draw. A decisively unsatisfying outcome. Might I not persuade you to play with me again?
Ah, MistressMaster  , always a pleasure. Francel has told me all. His is a tremendous task indeed to rebuild the Firmament, but I doubt not but that he will succeed.

Despite what some may say of my little brother, I know better than any that he is possessed of great fortitude. Nonetheless, I would be grateful if one such as you were to keep a watchful eye over him.
Want to go to Lyhe Mheg, do you? Very well, just close your eyes! Hee hee!
Awww, leaving already? You ought to stay and play a little longer!
Oh, hullo! If you are hoping to peruse our selection of festive wares, I am afraid they are not quite ready!
I'm afraid we're not quite ready to open for business. Pray come back a bit later, and I shall be happy to serve you.
My apologies, madamsir, but I do not yet have any traditional Heavensturn souvenirs to offer. But fear not─our good-bearers should arrive ere long.
Come on! You won't get hurt!
G-Give me just a moment!
I'll keep the wood safe. I'll keep everyone safe─just you watch!
So much water...and so many flowers! One day, I'll make Amh Araeng look just like this!
The sweets here are tasty...but the ones my mum makes are tasty too!
Well met, adventurer. You have the honor of addressing Aurvael de Haillenarte, second son of Count Baurendouin, and the man who will one day play a leading role in the future of Ishgard!

Ah, my dear adventurer. It pains me to have to tell you this, but due to unforeseen difficulties, House Haillenarte has been forced to suspend the expeditions to the Diadem. And we were so close to restoring our house's good name...

But take heart! For my younger brother Francel has won an office of moment in the Holy See, and ere long I shall conceive of another brilliant initiative to raise House Haillenarte to hithertofore unseen heights of glory!
My lord Aurvael is nothing if not an optimistic man. Even so, I cannot help but worry for his well-being.
He had poured his all into the Diadem, only to have his efforts cut short. I can only pray his fortunes take a turn for the better, and soon.
My apologies, my ladylord, but entry to the Firmament is restricted at this time.
Will you be heading to the Firmament, my ladylord? Just say the word, and I will show you through.
Our thanks for contributing to the reconstruction effort, my ladylord. Will you be leaving the Firmament now?
I feel as though something could be done to make the work environment more pleasant for all. Perhaps I shall take this up with the foreman...
Seeing all those people together, smiling and applauding... Brings a tear to the eye, it does.
Still not quite sure how I'll do my part for Eulmore, but I'll think of something.
We've all taken our lesson to heart. No need to worry about us─or to draw your weapon, thank you.
...Also, our convoluted plan turned out to be just as much work as taking the job seriously, in the end, so there's that.

When the time comes for the reconstruction work to recommence, I shall make another announcement. Meanwhile, my friend, I bid you rest and recover your strength. There shall most assuredly be much and more to be done.
Have you any Allied Seals? If so, Latool Ja have many interesting objects to trade with you.
Thanks to you beating Siegfried, Celestium stay with Royse and Martyn find work for blue mages. Everyone a winner! Except Siegfried, of course.

Our retinue has made the journey from Ishgard, in the hope of helping the people of Eorzea express their deepest feelings, during this season of romance. We shall do our utmost to give succor to those troubled by matters of the heart.
Enjoying the festivities, I trust. If you have not yet done so, why not have your affinity divined? Your affinity divined! Let us all celebrate this wondrous day of love together!
We're lucky you showed up when you did. I'm not sure what we could've done to hold back the Ruby Weapon without you.

I'm celebratory chief in addition to site chief...which means that Anogg and Konogg are going to do their part, the carnival is going to be a rousing success, and you are all going to have fun, dammit.
All finished in the Empty for the time being? Jolly good! Should you need to return at any point, we shall have all of the necessary supplies at your disposal.

I'm pleased to say that our excavating operations have commenced. While my husband and son spearhead the search for the stone tablets, I shall see to it they have all the support they require here at the Stopple.

Such joy I felt upon learning that the first stela had been found! Of course, this is merely the beginning, and as we descend deeper into the caverns, logistical support shall become ever more vital. Behind every successful expedition there is a well-run encampment, oh yes!
From talismans to shrines and everything in between, the Stopple is now splendidly appointed. We could not have made it so without your kind help, good madamsir!
Those stricken remain in grave condition, alas. Though the rest of us have taken up their responsibilities, I can only hope they are back at full strength before long.
It's always a pleasure to trade with those willing to aid our cause! We are fortunate indeed to have your cooperation.
Is it true that the great serpent has selected you as its vassal? Ah, yes. I sense an air of greatness about you. It is no small wonder you were granted such an honor!

We are truly blessed to have the Viis of Fanow as neighbors. Due to our mutual appreciation of the wonders of the forest and desire to protect Ronkan tradition, we feel that they are very much kindred spirits.
Can you hear it? That is the voice of the forest... It whispers to us the knowledge of the divine. And if you listen closely, it can even be heard to utter, “la-hee!”
This vase was recovered during one of our excavations. It appears to be of Ronkan design, but perhaps more interesting is this whistle which was found inside.
And perhaps most interesting of all is that when you blow on the whistle, from somewhere within the vase comes the great serpent! How long has it been dwelling within this artifact?
That this plague has come to the Stopple is a tragedy indeed...but the tragedy would be greater still if the great serpent were to become afflicted as well! Oh, I shiver with fright at the thought!
Welcome back, the both of you. I trust that our chicken situation is under control?
My visions have told me that it is you I must count on to ensure this year's Hatchingtide goes off without a hitch.
Why, I've never seen so many smiling faces! Be proud, my friend, for you have brought joy to many a child this Hatchingtide.
A happy Hatchingtide to you, my friend! I'm afraid we're still in the midst of preparing for the festivities. Pray come back a bit later, yes?
If you require transport to Gangos, I would be more than happy to take you.
Board the airship to the Doman Enclave?
A few days past, I went to watch a performance at the Mujikoza, and I was seated next to a rather outlandish but very handsome young man.

We engaged in some light conversation, and he explained that he is an actor himself, with the Majestic Theater Company. In fact, he is currently rehearsing for their latest production, though I expect he'll be finishing soon. Not that I'm following him around or anything! Perish the thought!
Is it true that you actually managed to defeat the Ruby Weapon? If only I could've seen that for myself!
The thick clouds and swirling winds have kept these isles isolated from the outside world for ages. As a result, there are creatures here like none other.
By the same token, this isolation also means the place has yet to be divested of its natural bounty. It's a veritable treasure trove of resources, as the Ishgardians have quickly discovered.
Of late, we see many a visiting forager using a most peculiar contraption. To be able to lay a beast low and reduce it to a heap of resources in one fell swoop... I am impressed, I must allow.
Owin' to the unstable aether, the environment of these isles can change as sudden as a gust. That's a sure recipe for aether sickness, let me tell you, and it doesn't make our work easy.

Our ship, the Bounty, was torn apart by the winds of the Diadem. Though we survived the crash, others were not so fortunate...and in the days that followed, still others fell victim to the beasts which roam these isles.
At the time, we thought we might have to spend the rest of our lives here, which is why we set about constructing this camp from the wreckage.

These days, there's no shortage of travelers come to forage these isles for their resources. At the Holy See's request, we offer them the use of our outpost, that they might rest and resupply─and retreat, should they find themselves overmatched.
To look at the Diadem now, you wouldn't think it used to be a place of danger and death, home to fiends that haunt your very nightmares.
But the promise of riches once drew many a sky pirate and adventurer here, and here they fought a vicious horde of ufitis. Not all lived to tell the tale.
The safety that we enjoy now, we owe in no small part to those courageous souls. We must see to it that their sacrifice isn't forgotten.

Recent changes in the aether have made the Diadem considerably safer than it was before, and it now throngs with those seeking to avail themselves of its wealth of resources. Nonetheless, the only thing that is truly certain about these isles is their uncertainty, and you would do well to tread warily.
It's well known that Triple Triad originated from the mysterious homeland of the Crystal Exarch, but now they're saying that the Warrior of Darkness hails from the selfsame place.
In hopes of playing with herhim one day, I have been practicing whenever I have spare time. Perhaps you would care to indulge me in a match?

Years ago, a new arrival came who brought Triple Triad cards with him. As we had little in the way of amusement here, the game quickly grew in popularity. When you have a moment, we must have a match.
Hah, victory is mine! With a little more practice, I daresay I shall be fit to challenge the Warrior of Darkness herselfhimself!
Ack, it appears I've lost... Strange, though. It doesn't feel so frustrating to be bested by you.
Well now, was that not a contest for the ages! With an opponent such as you, one would never grow bored!
I hear that Triple Triad is popular among the Majestic Theater Company, so I took up the game myself.
Oh, I'm dreadfully sorry, but I think that promising young actor I've been hoping to speak with will be passing by soon. Perhaps another time.
Oh, I say! That was easier than I thought it would be, though I suspect it may have merely been because of beginner's luck. Perhaps we should play another hand?
It seems I still have much to learn. Would you humor this poor novice by playing another hand?
Considering how evenly matched we seemed to be, I'd say a draw was a fair result. I wonder who would emerge the victor were we to play again?
Welcome back,  . Oh, but I can scarcely wait to share with you all I have seen and felt this Hatchingtide!
It is because of you and the bonds you have forged that we were able to bring smiles to the faces of so many children this year. I thank you from the bottom of my heart.
Julchiezain and Lycelle knew each other long before coming here. They may argue a lot, but they're really the best of friends.
You're an honest-to-gods hero, right? Please, teach us how to be strong like you!
Yes? Is there something you require?
Me? I salvage materials left over from the reconstruction and sell 'em cheap. Ain't much, but it's a livin', and it lets me do my bit for my fellow man.
Have you more tales to share? ...No? Well, should anything come to mind, I shall be most eager to hear it!
Should I go over there myself, perhaps? 'Tis true I am needed here to finish the plans, but at this rate we'll never find anyone versed in the trades to assist us...
Hm. You look like you know your trade. Mind if I take some measurements?
Neillemard does try to keep the others from going on about weighty tools and firm grasps and so on. Problem is, I don't think they even realize that they're doing it.
Oh, it's not that I don't know how to improve your tool─I've got too many ideas, if anything. It's more a matter of thinking them through before putting them to parchment.
...Unless you'd like to provide us some more parchment?

Not that I've encountered many dragons, but Ehll Tou is...rather different from what I had expected. For one, she isn't the least bit intimidating. Instead of a dragon, it feels as though I'm in the presence of an ordinary girl─albeit a smug one.
I'm not so clever as the others, but I'm great with my hands, if you know what I mean. Give me a few moments with any tool, no matter the size, and─
Bugger, was that one of the things Neillemard told me not to say? There are so many, it's hard to keep track.
They say there used to be a couple who had a farm in the central highlands. By the sweat of their brows, they came to grow the finest rolanberries in the land.
Yet though they were blessed with bountiful harvests, they weren't blessed with children. And so, when they became too old to work, they donated their farm to the church.
Since then, the farm's been run by men of the cloth, and the profits are used to operate this orphanage. And that's how the place got its name.
Even without being asked, the children help us with various chores about the orphanage. They have good hearts, all of them.
I've no children of my own─before this, they were as strange beasts to me. But now, I can't think of anything more precious than the little ones' smiles.
To know that the blood I shed helped to protect these irreplaceable lives... This is what makes me feel proudest to have been a knight.
I used to dream of becoming a great hero who fought dragons and saved the realm.
But you've already gone and done all that, so now I need another goal. Yes, perhaps I shall become the greatest artisan in all of Ishgard!
Thanks to you, Julchiezain isn't so obsessed with becoming a great hero anymore. He now knows there are other ways to do his part─while earning good coin besides.
I have the honor of bein' captain of the Endeavor. If you've ever dreamed of fishin' on the high seas, you'd best head to the Fishermen's Guild.
I reckon there are fish out there that not even Wawalago has seen the scales of, and I mean to have every last one of them grace the decks of my ship.

Standing here, I see people from the most exotic locales of Eorzea cross my path. It's enough to make one want to leave this post and hop on a ship to some unexplored corner of the world. <sigh> One day perhaps...

A beginner doesn't need to worry about catching the rarest fish, only about catching as many different fish as they can. That's the only way they'll become masters. So I always recommend a lure that'll attract a wide variety of fish, just maybe not the most desirable ones.
The most tranquil moments of my life have all occurred when there was a ship under my feet and bait in the ocean. Nothing else comes close.

On one voyage not long ago, the ocean started glittering like the night sky. It wasn't stars in the waters, though─it was hundreds, if not thousands, of fish. It wasn't until after, when I was inspecting my catch, that I realized it might've been one of those spectral currents people whisper about.
A true fisher must devote his entire self to the craft. We've no time for love or dalliance─the sea and its creatures are all the companionship we need.
My apologies, but we only conduct business with trusted members of the House.
If you're looking to trade scrips for goods, you've come to the right place. Everything you see can be yours, provided you have enough to trade!
The members of the Majestic Theater Company are rather busy at present, so if you have some business with them, I suggest you wait here.
When my husband collapsed, I must confess that I feared the worst. But thanks to your timely aid, good madamsir, the remaining tablets have been found, and we carry on our work with renewed zeal!
To think that our ancestors likewise dedicated themselves to uncovering our past. And now we have finished what they began! Splendid is the only way to describe it, oh yes!
As you may have heard, we have unearthed a mystical whistle capable of calling forth the great serpent! Such power, however, must be used wisely, lest we incur its wrath.
For the great serpent, only the finest offerings will suffice, and none are finer than the variety of hats we have lovingly crafted for it.
I must say, Chaqurl has been looking rather glum of late.
Were the great serpent to bless him with divine light, I am sure the smile would return to his face!
I simply cannot wait to see what will be found in the caves next. Truth be told, I can barely contain my excitement!
Alla doody, friend! That's how people greet each other in Slitherbough. Did you not know?
My friends tell me that a great serpent wearing a helmet appeared to lead them through the treacherous tunnels below!
Why, it led them clear of a cave-in that would have buried them alive! Praise be to the Great Serpent of Ronka!
I intend to teach Master Lanille's in-covation to all the Stewards! Surely it will protect us from harm!
Qitari legend has it that there are four stelae in all. We are but one step away from reclaiming the last piece of our legacy!
Father and Towarl are back on their feet again! Oh, how worried I was for them!
I am pleased to report that we have begun a preliminary investigation of the first level of the tunnels below. I am optimistic that we shall find signs of the first stela before long.
Pray accompany my boy to Slitherbough. I am hopeful that your friend Master Quinfort may be able to shed some light on the matter at hand.
I was skeptical at first, but I must admit the Night's Blessed have been most accommodating hosts.
Well, now...what have we here?
To think I would live to see the first piece of our forefathers' legacy reclaimed. Truly, this will go down as a momentous day in the annals of Qitari history...
I must travel to Fanow to thank our friends in person for all they have done on our behalf. Once the excavation effort is concluded, that is...
Scree! Scree!
